The optical properties of NCQDs are significantly influenced by nitrogen doping and surface states. The photoluminescence (PL) emission mainly originates from surface states, and nitrogen doping enhances the quantum yield by up to 33 %. The analysis suggests that the dominant role of surface functional groups over quantum confinement effects in determining optical properties improves DSSC performance by facilitating better light absorption and charge transport [78]. NCQDs synthesized hydrothermally from citric acid and urea show that specific nitrogen centers (graphitic and pyrrolic N-atoms) significantly influence their redox processes. The knowledge of these redox centres allows tuning of energetic levels for optoelectronic applications, such as DSSCs. The role of pyridinic N-atoms in optical and electrochemical responses is crucial for optimizing the performance of NCQDs in DSSCs [79]. An NCQDs/MoS2 heterostructure photodetector exhibits significant photo response across UV, visible, and NIR regions. The heterostructure provides responsivity of 4.31 AW−1, 26.73 AW−1, and 20.72 AW−1 at 325 nm, 532 nm, and 1064 nm wavelengths, respectively. The high external quantum efficiency (EQE) and fast response time demonstrate the potential of NCQDs in broad range photodetection applications [80]. N-GQDs combined with anatase TiO2 in a heterojunction-based photodetector show enhanced photoresponsivity by almost 2.5 times compared to pure TiO2-based photodetectors (Fig. 5
                     ). The improved performance is attributed to better light absorption and efficient charge transport mechanisms facilitated by the hybrid structure [81]. NCQDs exhibit strong solid-state emission due to surface functional groups that prevent π-π stacking interactions. Electrochemical control of PL enhancement in NCQD films can be achieved by modulating electrochemical potentials, enhancing their applicability in solid-state optoelectronic devices such as photodetectors [82]. These properties highlight the versatility and efficiency of NCQDs in enhancing the performance of DSSCs and photodetectors through improved light absorption, charge transport, and tunable optical responses. Table 1
                      shows the different characteristics of NCQDs utilized in applications.

A substrate, a conducting layer that is see-through, dyes, an electrolyte, a photo electrode, a counter electrode, and a sealing gasket are the standard components of a dye sensitized solar cell. Films of semiconductors, dye sensitizers, a layer of mesoporous TiO2, a redox electrolyte, a substrate that conducts electricity, and a counter electrode are the main parts of DSSCs (
                        Fig. 6

                        ).

NCQDs have recently emerged as promising candidates for performing the role of photodetectors due to their applications [195]. These nanomaterials provide outstanding PLE performance, high quantum yield and a green synthesis approach. Their distinctive electrical and optical features are attributed to the product incorporation of nitrogen atoms into the carbon lattice that provides additional energy levels in improving the absorption and emission of light (
                        Table 5

                        ) [196].
